<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900813-0094</DOCNO><DOCID>900813-0094.</DOCID><HL>   Western Union Corp.   Locks Out Workers   Amid Contract Talks</HL><DATE>08/13/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   WU LABOR</CO><LP>   UPPER SADDLE RIVER, N.J. (AP) -- Western Union Corp. onSaturday locked out 2,000 employees in the middle of contracttalks with their union.   The company did not indicate whether the workers would berehired if it signs a new contract with their union, theCommunications Workers of America, which represents a totalof 2,500 workers at Western Union.</LP><TEXT>   Western Union said the replacements would not affect itsmoney-transfer, telex, electronic mail and paper-basedmessage services.   &quot;We sincerely regret that, in the absence of a unioncontract, we have reluctantly had to take this defensiveaction,&quot; said Robert J. Amman, Western Union president andchief executive officer. &quot;We cannot operate under theever-present threat of an employee strike while continuing tobear the cost required to ensure that the company wouldsurvive one.&quot;   Western Union has a total of 3,400 employees. The CWArepresents operators, customer relations clerks, clericalworkers and field technicians.   Dan Beckstead, the chief union negotiator, deplored thelockout, saying the union had not given the company anyindication it intends to strike.   &quot;In fact, we told them we wanted to continue to negotiatein an attempt to reach an agreement,&quot; Mr. Beckstead said. CWAworkers have authorized their leadership to call a strike.   Western Union said many of the replaced CWA workers werefrom its central telephone bureaus in Bridgeton, Miss., andReno, Nev.; its computer centers in Middletown, Va., andBridgeton.   It temporarily replaced them with workers from WesternUnion headquarters and trained temporary replacements, thecompany said.   The company has been negotiating with representatives ofthe CWA since July 23. The previous two-year contract expiredAug. 6, but management and union negotiators have continuedto meet to try to agree on a new pact.</TEXT></DOC>